  <p>
    Rideshare crashes are uniquely confusing. When you're in a regular car crash, there's one driver and one insurance policy on each side. When an Uber or Lyft is involved, the insurance picture fractures into stages, coverage limits shift depending on what the driver was doing at the exact moment of impact, and the rideshare company works hard to stay out of it entirely.
  </p>

  <p>
    You don't need to figure this out alone. That's our job.
  </p>

  <h2>The Three Insurance Stages</h2>

  <p>
    Both Uber and Lyft structure their insurance around three stages tied to the driver's app status at the time of the crash. Each stage offers different coverage levels, and the difference can be hundreds of thousands of dollars.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Stage 1: App on, no ride accepted.</strong> The driver is logged into the app and available for rides, but hasn't accepted one. Coverage is minimal. Uber and Lyft provide contingent liability coverage that only kicks in if the driver's personal insurance doesn't cover the claim. Limits are typically $50,000 per person and $100,000 per crash for bodily injury.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Stage 2: Ride accepted, en route to passenger.</strong> The driver has accepted a ride request and is heading to pick up the passenger. The rideshare company's liability coverage is active, typically $1 million. Uninsured and underinsured motorist coverage also applies.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Stage 3: Passenger in the vehicle.</strong> Full coverage. The rideshare company provides $1 million in liability coverage plus uninsured/underinsured motorist coverage. This is the most protection available.
  </p>

  <h2>The Independent Contractor Problem</h2>

  <p>
    Uber and Lyft classify their drivers as independent contractors, not employees. This classification serves a strategic purpose: it creates a legal barrier between the company and the driver's actions. If the driver is an independent contractor, the argument goes, the company isn't directly responsible for the driver's negligence.
  </p>

  <p>
    Arizona's transportation network company laws address this dynamic to some extent, requiring rideshare companies to maintain insurance coverage during active rides regardless of the driver's employment classification. But the liability question gets complicated fast, especially in Stage 1 situations where coverage is minimal.
  </p>

  <p>
    We navigate these distinctions for every rideshare case. The legal question of who's responsible and the insurance question of who pays aren't always the same answer.
  </p>

  <h2>Passengers, Other Drivers, and Pedestrians</h2>

  <p>
    Rideshare crashes don't just affect passengers. If you were driving your own car and a rideshare driver hit you, the applicable insurance depends on the driver's app status at that moment. If you were a pedestrian or cyclist hit by a rideshare driver, the same staging rules apply.
  </p>

  <p>
    We handle claims from all perspectives: passengers injured during rides, other motorists hit by rideshare drivers, pedestrians and cyclists struck by distracted rideshare drivers, and rideshare drivers themselves who were injured by other motorists during a ride.
  </p>

  <h2>Rideshare Crashes in the Phoenix Metro</h2>

  <p>
    Phoenix is one of the largest rideshare markets in the country. Uber and Lyft drivers are everywhere: downtown Phoenix, Scottsdale, Tempe's entertainment district, Sky Harbor Airport, and increasingly throughout the West Valley as Buckeye and Goodyear grow. The high volume of rideshare vehicles means more crashes involving these drivers.
  </p>

  <p>
    Airport pickups and drop-offs along Sky Harbor's access roads are a common crash location. Late-night rides from entertainment districts in Scottsdale and Tempe see elevated crash rates. Even routine residential pickups in the West Valley involve distracted drivers navigating unfamiliar neighborhoods while following GPS directions.
  </p>

  <h2>Getting the Records That Matter</h2>

  <p>
    Rideshare companies maintain detailed records of every ride: when the driver logged in, when they accepted the ride, the route taken, speed data, and when the trip ended. These records are essential for establishing which insurance stage applies and reconstructing the crash.
  </p>

  <p>
    We request this data immediately after taking your case. Rideshare companies will produce it, but they don't volunteer it. Legal demand is usually required. The faster we request it, the more complete the records tend to be.
  </p>

